description:
# Create Custom SCSS Overrides

Override Just the Docs theme variables to apply purple/indigo branding.

## Implementation

1. Create `docs/_sass/custom/custom.scss`
2. Add the following variable overrides:
   ```scss
   // Color scheme
   $primary-color: #6366f1;
   $hover-color: #4f46e5;
   $background-color: #ffffff;
   $surface-color: #f9fafb;
   $border-color: #e5e7eb;
   $text-color: #111827;
   $text-secondary: #6b7280;

   // Typography
   $base-font-family: 'Inter', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, Oxygen-Sans, Ubuntu, Cantarell, "Helvetica Neue", sans-serif;
   $code-font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', 'SF Mono', Monaco, "Cascadia Code", "Roboto Mono", Consolas, "Courier New", monospace;

   // Layout
   $sidebar-width: 280px;
   $border-radius: 6px;

   // Spacing
   $spacing-unit: 8px;
   ```
3. Import after theme styles

## Files to Create

- `docs/_sass/custom/custom.scss` - Theme variable overrides

## Verification

- SCSS file is valid syntax
- Variables override theme defaults

# Implement Lunr.js search

Add client-side search functionality using Lunr.js.

## Files to create

1. **`docs/_includes/search.html`** - Search input UI:
```html
<div class="search-container">
  <input type="text" id="search-input" placeholder="Search documentation...">
  <div id="search-results"></div>
</div>
```

2. **`docs/assets/js/search.js`** - Lunr.js implementation:
```javascript
// Build Lunr index from all pages
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  const idx = lunr(function() {
    this.ref('id');
    this.field('title', {boost: 10});
    this.field('content');

    // Add all pages to index
    // (implementation will iterate through page data)
  });

  const searchInput = document.getElementById('search-input');
  const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('search-results');

  searchInput.addEventListener('input', function() {
    const query = this.value;
    if (query.length < 2) {
      resultsDiv.innerHTML = '';
      return;
    }

    const results = idx.search(query);
    resultsDiv.innerHTML = results.map(r => `
      <div class="search-result">
        <a href="${r.ref}">${r.doc.title}</a>
      </div>
    `).join('');
  });
});
```

3. **Update `docs/_layouts/default.html`** to include search:
- Add `{% include search.html %}` in header
- Add script tags for lunr.js and search.js
- Add search CSS styles

## Implementation approach

1. Download or CDN link Lunr.js library
2. Build index from Jekyll's page.data on page load
3. Configure search to return matching pages with snippets
4. Style search results dropdown

## Verification

- Typing in search box shows matching pages
- Search works on all markdown content
- Search results are clickable links
